WEBVTT

1
00:00:38.627 --> 00:00:40.629
<i><font color="#ffff80">NEKHORVICH:</font> Well, Dmitri.</i>

2
00:00:41.129 --> 00:00:43.173
<i>Every search for a hero</i>

3
00:00:43.507 --> 00:00:46.843
<i>must begin with something
that every hero requires,</i>

4
00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:49.304
<i>a villain.</i>

5
00:00:50.097 --> 00:00:54.893
<i>Therefore
in a search for our hero, Bellerophon</i>

6
00:00:55.143 --> 00:00:56.937
<i>we created a monster</i>

7
00:00:59.773 --> 00:01:01.024
<i>Chimera.</i>

8
00:01:01.108 --> 00:01:02.109
<font color="#ff8000">[INJECTING]</font>

9
00:01:05.487 --> 00:01:08.198
<i>I beg you, Dmitri, come to Sydney</i>

10
00:01:08.282 --> 00:01:10.993
<i>and accompany me
to Atlanta immediately.</i>

11
00:01:11.285 --> 00:01:12.661
<i>However we travel,</i>

12
00:01:12.703 --> 00:01:16.915
<i>I must arrive at my destination
within 20 hours of departure.</i>

13
00:01:23.171 --> 00:01:24.798
<font color="#ff8000">[CHILDREN GIGGLING]</font>

14
00:01:29.553 --> 00:01:32.097
<font color="#ffff80">CHILDREN:</font> ♪ Ring around the Rosie ♪

15
00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:34.891
♪ A pocket full of posies ♪

16
00:01:34.975 --> 00:01:37.894
♪ Ashes, ashes ♪

17
00:01:37.978 --> 00:01:40.522
♪ We all fall down ♪

18
00:01:40.606 --> 00:01:41.607
<font color="#ff8000">[LAUGHING]</font>

19
00:01:48.989 --> 00:01:51.533
<i><font color="#ffff80">CAPTAIN OVER PA:</font> Folks,
we're two and a half hours from Atlanta.</i>

20
00:01:51.575 --> 00:01:55.370
<i>Look out your window now. We have
a great view of the Rocky Mountains.</i>

21
00:01:56.622 --> 00:02:00.876
You keep staring at that watch
as if your life depended on it, Doctor.

22
00:02:01.084 --> 00:02:03.045
Well, yes.

23
00:02:03.462 --> 00:02:05.589
I suppose I'm a bit anxious.

24
00:02:05.881 --> 00:02:08.133
You'll soon be with old friends.

25
00:02:08.425 --> 00:02:10.927
I'm with an old friend now, Dmitri.

26
00:02:12.054 --> 00:02:15.098
I'm sorry it couldn't be
under happier circumstances.

27
00:02:15.223 --> 00:02:16.558
I'm sorry too.

28
00:02:16.933 --> 00:02:19.186
You are sorry, and I am sorry.

29
00:02:23.023 --> 00:02:25.901
You don't know Gradski thought the
world of you.

30
00:02:26.151 --> 00:02:27.361
Did he

31
00:02:28.362 --> 00:02:29.488
know

32
00:02:29.780 --> 00:02:32.407
before the end
that you two had succeeded?

33
00:02:32.449 --> 00:02:34.826
Yes, he knew. Just.

34
00:02:35.827 --> 00:02:37.788
Not in time to save him?

35
00:02:38.413 --> 00:02:39.414
No.

36
00:02:40.040 --> 00:02:43.585
After you've been infected with Chimera
for 20 hours

37
00:02:43.669 --> 00:02:45.420
nothing can save you

38
00:02:45.837 --> 00:02:47.631
not even Bellerophon.

39
00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.926
You can carry them together

40
00:02:52.552 --> 00:02:53.720
safely?

41
00:02:53.762 --> 00:02:54.846
Yes.

42
00:02:55.889 --> 00:02:59.851
And you'll get us to safe place with them
in Atlanta, thank God.

43
00:03:01.395 --> 00:03:02.604
<i><font color="#ffff80">CAPTAIN OVER PA:</font>
This is your Captain again.</i>

44
00:03:02.688 --> 00:03:06.274
<i>We've experienced a slight
but abrupt drop in cabin pressure.</i>

45
00:03:06.358 --> 00:03:09.069
As a precaution,
I've released the oxygen masks.

46
00:03:09.111 --> 00:03:12.280
<i>Please put them on, sit back, relax.</i>

47
00:03:12.322 --> 00:03:14.616
<i>There's nothing to worry about.</i>

48
00:03:17.536 --> 00:03:18.954
Are you concerned?

49
00:03:19.705 --> 00:03:21.248
Not so far.

50
00:03:21.623 --> 00:03:23.125
Just put on your oxygen mask.

51
00:03:23.166 --> 00:03:25.502
- I'll see what's going on.
- Okay.

52
00:03:32.634 --> 00:03:36.930
Denver Center,
this is Transpac 2207, 747 heavy.

53
00:03:37.889 --> 00:03:40.100
We're unable to maintain cabin
pressurization.

54
00:03:40.142 --> 00:03:43.478
We've initiated a descent to 1-6000.

55
00:03:44.396 --> 00:03:45.939
Captain...

56
00:04:13.759 --> 00:04:14.843
God.

57
00:04:26.772 --> 00:04:29.357
It seems we have a problem, Dmitri.

58
00:04:29.649 --> 00:04:31.735
You keep calling me Dmitri.

59
00:04:33.028 --> 00:04:34.821
You really shouldn't.

60
00:04:35.447 --> 00:04:37.407
You are not Dmitri?

61
00:04:50.837 --> 00:04:51.838
No.

62
00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:55.258
Wallis,

63
00:04:55.675 --> 00:04:57.260
hold on to this.

64
00:05:08.021 --> 00:05:10.398
Ulrich, remember to pull the...

65
00:05:13.568 --> 00:05:16.279
Remember to pull the NO2 tank
and dump it.

66
00:05:16.363 --> 00:05:17.989
All done, chief.

67
00:05:21.117 --> 00:05:22.994
<i><font color="#ffff80">AUTOPILOT:</font> Terrain. Terrain.</i>

68
00:05:23.078 --> 00:05:24.079
<font color="#ff8000">[ALARM BEEPING]</font>

69
00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.414
<i>Pull up. Pull up. Terrain.</i>

70
00:05:30.585 --> 00:05:32.420
<font color="#ffff80">MAN:</font> Seven nine nine!

71
00:05:32.587 --> 00:05:35.465
<i><font color="#ffff80">MAN 2:</font>
Checkpoint Charlie, three, two, one!</i>

72
00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:37.008
Go!

73
00:05:44.099 --> 00:05:45.851
<i><font color="#ffff80">AUTOPILOT:</font> Terrain. Terrain.</i>

74
00:05:45.934 --> 00:05:47.644
<i>Pull up. Pull up.</i>

75
00:05:48.019 --> 00:05:49.604
<i>Terrain. Terrain.</i>

76
00:05:49.688 --> 00:05:51.982
<i>Pull up. Pull up.</i>

77
00:05:54.734 --> 00:05:56.069
<font color="#ff8000">[SCREAMING]</font>

78
00:08:29.639 --> 00:08:31.433
<font color="#ff8000">[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]</font>

79
00:08:45.530 --> 00:08:46.656
<i><font color="#ff8000">[MISSION: IMPOSSIBLE
THEME</i> PLAYING]</font>

80
00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:47.741
<font color="#ff8000">[SCOFFS]</font>

81
00:09:17.437 --> 00:09:18.855
<i><font color="#ffff80">SWANBECK ON EARPIECE:</font>
Good morning, Mr. Hunt.</i>

82
00:09:18.938 --> 00:09:20.815
<i>Your mission,
should you choose to accept it</i>

83
00:09:20.857 --> 00:09:23.068
<i>involves the recovery of a stolen item</i>

84
00:09:23.151 --> 00:09:24.944
<i>designated Chimera.</i>

85
00:09:24.986 --> 00:09:27.614
<i>You may select any two team members
but it is essential</i>

86
00:09:27.655 --> 00:09:31.159
<i>that the third team
member be Nyah Nordoff-Hall.</i>

87
00:09:31.242 --> 00:09:32.827
<i>She is a civilian</i>

88
00:09:32.911 --> 00:09:35.371
<i>and a highly capable professional thief.</i>

89
00:09:35.455 --> 00:09:38.124
<i>You have 48 hours
to recruit Miss Nordoff-Hall</i>

90
00:09:38.166 --> 00:09:40.919
<i>and meet me in Seville
to receive your assignment.</i>

91
00:09:41.002 --> 00:09:44.506
<i>As always, should you or any member
of your IMF team be caught or killed</i>

92
00:09:44.589 --> 00:09:48.176
<i>the Secretary will disavow
all knowledge of your actions.</i>

93
00:09:48.426 --> 00:09:50.929
<i>And, Mr. Hunt,
the next time you go on holiday</i>

94
00:09:51.012 --> 00:09:54.099
<i>please let us know where you're going.</i>

95
00:09:54.182 --> 00:09:55.850
<i><font color="#ffff80">WOMAN ON EARPIECE:</font>
This message will self-destruct</i>

96
00:09:55.892 --> 00:09:57.227
<i>in five seconds.</i>

97
00:09:57.310 --> 00:09:59.687
If I let you know where I'm going

98
00:10:00.313 --> 00:10:02.524
then I won't be on holiday.

99
00:10:41.479 --> 00:10:42.939
<font color="#ff8000">[FLAMENCO MUSIC PLAYING]</font>

100
00:12:56.948 --> 00:12:57.949
<font color="#ff8000">[CROWD APPLAUDING]</font>

101
00:13:37.739 --> 00:13:39.490
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> I see you found it.

102
00:13:42.952 --> 00:13:44.412
What are you doing here?

103
00:13:44.495 --> 00:13:47.081
Think you're the only one
who can pick a lock?

104
00:13:49.292 --> 00:13:51.502
Not just a pretty face after all.

105
00:13:51.627 --> 00:13:52.628
<font color="#ff8000">[DOOR OPENING]</font>

106
00:13:52.795 --> 00:13:53.796
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN HUMMING]</font>

107
00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:11.564
Do you mind if I'm on top?

108
00:14:12.607 --> 00:14:14.942
Either way works for me.

109
00:14:30.833 --> 00:14:31.834
<font color="#ff8000">[DOOR OPENING]</font>

110
00:14:32.627 --> 00:14:33.628
<font color="#ff8000">[DOOR CLOSING]</font>

111
00:14:39.467 --> 00:14:42.345
- You'll never find it there.
- Damn it.

112
00:14:44.806 --> 00:14:47.058
- Find what?
- His ex's Bulgari necklace.

113
00:14:47.141 --> 00:14:49.560
It goes up for auction on Tuesday.

114
00:14:53.815 --> 00:14:56.859
And are you going to tell me where it is?

115
00:14:59.028 --> 00:15:00.321
Far left.

116
00:15:12.375 --> 00:15:14.752
This is very disconcerting.

117
00:15:15.336 --> 00:15:18.506
Hey, you put me here.
I just do as I'm told.

118
00:15:19.507 --> 00:15:20.675
Right.

119
00:15:46.701 --> 00:15:47.910
Now

120
00:15:48.786 --> 00:15:52.039
who are you
and what's it gonna cost me?

121
00:15:52.582 --> 00:15:54.167
I wouldn't do that.

122
00:15:54.375 --> 00:15:55.501
What?

123
00:15:55.585 --> 00:15:56.586
<font color="#ff8000">[ALARM BLARING]</font>

124
00:15:57.253 --> 00:15:58.296
That.

125
00:15:59.547 --> 00:16:00.548
<font color="#ff8000">[MEN SHOUTING IN SPANISH]</font>

126
00:16:06.387 --> 00:16:07.388
<font color="#ff8000">[TALKING IN SPANISH]</font>

127
00:16:08.055 --> 00:16:09.807
Mr. Keys, it is you.

128
00:16:09.891 --> 00:16:13.019
It is Mr. Keys, our security engineer.
Apologize!

129
00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:15.062
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> No, no need to apologize.

130
00:16:15.688 --> 00:16:18.900
Miss Hall, my associate,
has your necklace in a very safe place

131
00:16:18.983 --> 00:16:22.612
but obviously we do feel the alarm
should have gone off a little sooner.

132
00:16:22.695 --> 00:16:24.655
Isn't that right, Miss Hall?

133
00:16:24.864 --> 00:16:28.284
Oh, absolutely.
Much, much too long, I'd say.

134
00:16:31.204 --> 00:16:35.791
We'd recommend resetting the sensors
to respond to a lighter load.

135
00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.794
How do you feel about 40 kilos,
Miss Hall?

136
00:16:39.003 --> 00:16:40.254
Perfect.

137
00:16:42.423 --> 00:16:43.716
Shall we?

138
00:16:46.969 --> 00:16:48.554
Miss Hall,

139
00:16:49.889 --> 00:16:52.225
haven't you forgotten something?

140
00:16:56.771 --> 00:17:00.441
What are you trying to do, senorita,
rob me?

141
00:17:00.608 --> 00:17:02.944
The thought had crossed my mind.

142
00:17:04.779 --> 00:17:06.239
<font color="#ffff80">NYAH:</font> I'm missing something here,

143
00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:08.199
aside from my
half million pound necklace.

144
00:17:08.282 --> 00:17:10.743
Even after I screwed up the job, I
could have walked out with the thing.

145
00:17:10.785 --> 00:17:11.994
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> At least you walked.

146
00:17:12.078 --> 00:17:14.747
If you weren't going to let me get away
with it, why did you watch me do it?

147
00:17:14.789 --> 00:17:16.207
I wanted to see how good you were.

148
00:17:16.290 --> 00:17:18.793
I was hoping we might work together.

149
00:17:18.834 --> 00:17:20.461
Sounds terrific.

150
00:17:21.045 --> 00:17:22.046
<font color="#ff8000">[SPEAKING IN SPANISH]</font>

151
00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:27.134
Now be serious.
Whatever you're talking about,

152
00:17:27.218 --> 00:17:28.970
you couldn't want me
after that performance.

153
00:17:29.053 --> 00:17:32.431
- You didn't do that badly.
- You apologizing for me?

154
00:17:32.974 --> 00:17:34.767
Quite the gentleman.

155
00:17:35.017 --> 00:17:36.394
Not really.

156
00:17:37.562 --> 00:17:39.438
I triggered the alarm.

157
00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:40.481
<font color="#ff8000">[ALARM BLARING]</font>

158
00:17:42.858 --> 00:17:44.360
Sorry.

159
00:17:48.823 --> 00:17:51.284
I don't do laundry, cook

160
00:17:51.576 --> 00:17:53.995
or put up with cheeky bastards
who set me up on their territory

161
00:17:54.078 --> 00:17:55.830
so they can poach on mine.

162
00:17:55.955 --> 00:17:57.331
<font color="#ff8000">[TIRES SCREECHING]</font>

163
00:18:12.096 --> 00:18:13.097
<font color="#ff8000">[PHONE RINGING]</font>

164
00:18:20.229 --> 00:18:22.398
- Hello.
<i>- <font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Hi.</i>

165
00:18:22.857 --> 00:18:25.026
Would you mind slowing down?

166
00:18:27.695 --> 00:18:30.615
Where did you get this number?
I don't even have it.

167
00:18:32.575 --> 00:18:33.993
Would you like it?

168
00:18:42.793 --> 00:18:44.253
<font color="#ff8000">[PHONE RINGING]</font>

169
00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:55.890
Pull over and listen to me, will you?
Just listen.

170
00:18:55.973 --> 00:18:58.726
- Listen to what?
- I need your help.

171
00:18:58.809 --> 00:19:01.896
- I think you could use mine.
- Your help?

172
00:19:02.021 --> 00:19:03.397
What are you talking about?

173
00:19:03.439 --> 00:19:06.275
I'm talking about Scotland Yard, Interpol

174
00:19:06.442 --> 00:19:08.319
every Dutch authority.

175
00:19:09.195 --> 00:19:11.072
I can make them all go away.

176
00:19:11.155 --> 00:19:12.740
Oh, bloody hell.

177
00:19:12.823 --> 00:19:14.325
You're a spy!

178
00:19:14.742 --> 00:19:17.620
Well, if you want me,
you've gotta catch me.

179
00:19:39.725 --> 00:19:41.435
You having fun?

180
00:19:54.573 --> 00:19:55.741
Sorry.

181
00:20:01.247 --> 00:20:02.248
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN YELLING IN SPANISH]</font>

182
00:20:03.499 --> 00:20:04.750
Sorry.

183
00:20:05.793 --> 00:20:07.503
Watch the road.

184
00:20:07.586 --> 00:20:08.587
<font color="#ff8000">[CAR HONKING]</font>

185
00:20:08.671 --> 00:20:09.672
<font color="#ff8000">[SCREAMING]</font>

186
00:20:15.511 --> 00:20:16.512
<font color="#ff8000">[TRUCK HORN HONKING]</font>

187
00:20:20.808 --> 00:20:23.018
<font color="#ff8000">[TIRES SCREECHING]</font>

188
00:20:53.090 --> 00:20:54.091
<font color="#ff8000">[WHIMPERING]</font>

189
00:21:02.099 --> 00:21:04.393
<font color="#ff8000">[NYAH PANTING]</font>

190
00:21:11.859 --> 00:21:13.527
What's your name?

191
00:21:15.279 --> 00:21:16.655
Ethan Hunt.

192
00:21:17.823 --> 00:21:19.408
Well, Ethan Hunt

193
00:21:21.202 --> 00:21:23.913
what is it you want to talk to me about?

194
00:21:24.872 --> 00:21:26.916
A lot more than I thought.

195
00:21:30.544 --> 00:21:32.463
Awfully short notice.

196
00:21:33.255 --> 00:21:35.549
Care to wait a decent interval?

197
00:21:36.258 --> 00:21:38.093
Who wants to be decent?

198
00:22:01.617 --> 00:22:02.618
<font color="#ff8000">[SIGHS]</font>

199
00:22:35.609 --> 00:22:38.112
So what have you got against spies?

200
00:22:38.612 --> 00:22:41.240
When they've got
your recruiting technique

201
00:22:41.282 --> 00:22:42.783
nothing.

202
00:22:44.285 --> 00:22:47.830
- This wasn't exactly by the book.
- They've got a book for this?

203
00:22:47.913 --> 00:22:50.332
They've got a book for everything.

204
00:22:51.584 --> 00:22:54.003
So this thing these blokes pinched...

205
00:22:54.295 --> 00:22:56.714
I don't know that they pinched it.

206
00:22:57.006 --> 00:22:59.633
I don't even know that they're blokes.

207
00:23:01.302 --> 00:23:03.178
What am I doing here?

208
00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:09.351
I thought I was supposed to be
some kind of thief to catch a thief.

209
00:23:09.643 --> 00:23:11.145
So did I.

210
00:23:12.563 --> 00:23:13.814
Sort of.

211
00:23:21.488 --> 00:23:23.490
Damn, you're beautiful.

212
00:23:49.683 --> 00:23:51.352
<font color="#ff8000">[CROWD CHANTING AND SINGING]</font>

213
00:24:29.306 --> 00:24:30.307
<font color="#ff8000">[DOOR OPENING]</font>

214
00:24:38.190 --> 00:24:39.775
Espresso? Cappuccino?

215
00:24:39.858 --> 00:24:41.318
No, thanks.

216
00:24:42.111 --> 00:24:43.404
Sit down.

217
00:24:44.655 --> 00:24:46.240
Festival's a pain in the ass.

218
00:24:46.323 --> 00:24:48.659
Honoring their saints
by setting them on fire.

219
00:24:48.742 --> 00:24:51.078
Lets you know what they think of
saints, doesn't it?

220
00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:54.081
Damn near set me on fire
on my way over here.

221
00:24:56.583 --> 00:24:58.752
Sorry, I barged in on your vacation.

222
00:24:58.794 --> 00:25:02.923
- Sorry I didn't tell you where I was.
- Wouldn't be a vacation if you did.

223
00:25:02.965 --> 00:25:05.426
Well, you're sorry, and I'm sorry.

224
00:25:07.511 --> 00:25:10.889
- Why did you phrase it like that?
- Like what?

225
00:25:11.181 --> 00:25:13.225
"You're sorry. I'm sorry."

226
00:25:13.517 --> 00:25:14.518
<font color="#ff8000">[CHUCKLES]</font>

227
00:25:14.768 --> 00:25:16.270
You gotta be kidding.

228
00:25:23.694 --> 00:25:25.112
<i><font color="#ffff80">NEKHORVICH:</font> Well, Dmitri</i>

229
00:25:25.696 --> 00:25:27.740
<i>once again I need your help</i>

230
00:25:27.781 --> 00:25:29.992
<i>just as in the old days, huh?</i>

231
00:25:30.451 --> 00:25:34.163
<i>When you saved our lives,
saved our very sanity.</i>

232
00:25:35.789 --> 00:25:36.790
<i>Dmitri...</i>

233
00:25:38.250 --> 00:25:41.295
<i>We have this little problem.</i>

234
00:25:42.963 --> 00:25:44.840
<i>Every search for a hero</i>

235
00:25:45.507 --> 00:25:48.802
<i>must begin with something
that every hero requires,</i>

236
00:25:48.844 --> 00:25:50.179
<i>a villain.</i>

237
00:25:50.929 --> 00:25:55.309
<i>Therefore
in a search for our hero, Bellerophon</i>

238
00:25:55.976 --> 00:25:58.145
<i>we created a monster</i>

239
00:25:58.687 --> 00:25:59.938
<i>Chimera.</i>

240
00:26:01.148 --> 00:26:04.151
<i>I beg you, Dmitri, come to Sydney</i>

241
00:26:04.234 --> 00:26:07.696
<i>and accompany me to
Atlanta immediately.</i>

242
00:26:08.155 --> 00:26:09.823
<i>However we travel,</i>

243
00:26:09.907 --> 00:26:14.495
<i>I must arrive at my destination
within 20 hours of departure.</i>

244
00:26:15.579 --> 00:26:19.666
<i>I fear I can entrust this
to no one but you.</i>

245
00:26:20.334 --> 00:26:21.335
<i>Dmitri...</i>

246
00:26:22.086 --> 00:26:26.131
<i>As we say, I'm sorry, and you are sorry.</i>

247
00:26:26.590 --> 00:26:28.926
Do you have any idea what the hell
he's talking about?

248
00:26:29.009 --> 00:26:30.594
An idea? Yeah.

249
00:26:30.969 --> 00:26:33.680
- Like?
- It's a good idea to get him now.

250
00:26:33.931 --> 00:26:38.185
A bad idea to fly him on a commercial
carrier. Is he still in Sydney?

251
00:26:38.685 --> 00:26:41.021
Dr. Vladimir Nekhorvich is dead.

252
00:26:42.689 --> 00:26:46.193
So is his colleague Gradski,
but that happened earlier.

253
00:26:46.443 --> 00:26:48.695
We had Nekhorvich on a flight
from Sydney

254
00:26:48.779 --> 00:26:50.906
that crashed in the Rockies.

255
00:26:51.365 --> 00:26:52.449
Dead.

256
00:26:52.699 --> 00:26:54.701
Are you listening to me?

257
00:26:56.245 --> 00:26:59.123
If he didn't want to go anywhere
without me

258
00:27:00.415 --> 00:27:02.543
how did you get him on that flight?

259
00:27:02.584 --> 00:27:04.128
You were there.

260
00:27:11.718 --> 00:27:14.221
When I couldn't find you,
I had to replace you.

261
00:27:14.263 --> 00:27:16.598
Sean Ambrose was the obvious choice.

262
00:27:16.682 --> 00:27:19.101
He doubled you two or three times.

263
00:27:21.812 --> 00:27:24.064
- Twice.
- What did you think of him?

264
00:27:27.526 --> 00:27:31.655
We had reservations about each other.
It's a bit late to be asking me that.

265
00:27:31.738 --> 00:27:33.407
No, not necessarily.

266
00:27:33.448 --> 00:27:34.992
Airline records

267
00:27:36.034 --> 00:27:39.788
list a Captain Harold Macintosh
as the pilot of flight 2207.

268
00:27:40.289 --> 00:27:43.750
As far as the media and all the
governmental agencies are concerned

269
00:27:43.834 --> 00:27:46.420
Captain Macintosh died in the flight.

270
00:27:46.670 --> 00:27:48.463
But, in fact, he missed it.

271
00:27:49.173 --> 00:27:51.633
He did, however, make the next flight

272
00:27:51.925 --> 00:27:53.177
in cargo

273
00:27:53.886 --> 00:27:57.598
stuffed into a rather small suitcase,
considering his size.

274
00:27:58.515 --> 00:28:01.226
Someone on that flight
planned an operation

275
00:28:01.268 --> 00:28:03.520
designed to bring the plane down and
make it look like an accident.

276
00:28:03.604 --> 00:28:06.732
Someone skillful enough
to bring it off without a hitch.

277
00:28:08.275 --> 00:28:11.320
There's one thing we know
that Ambrose doesn't.

278
00:28:11.403 --> 00:28:14.865
Then you do think it was Ambrose?
You're not surprised?

279
00:28:15.365 --> 00:28:16.825
Sean feels he hasn't done the job

280
00:28:16.909 --> 00:28:18.827
unless he leaves a lot of hats
on the ground.

281
00:28:18.911 --> 00:28:20.454
The question is why.

282
00:28:20.537 --> 00:28:23.540
What was this Chimera
Nekhorvich was carrying?

283
00:28:24.791 --> 00:28:26.501
Only Ambrose knows that.

284
00:28:27.211 --> 00:28:30.797
In any case,
you must recover this Chimera

285
00:28:30.881 --> 00:28:32.633
and bring it to us.

286
00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:37.262
In order to do that, I've got to figure
out how he plans to make money on it.

287
00:28:37.304 --> 00:28:39.431
That is where Miss Hall comes in.

288
00:28:44.144 --> 00:28:45.479
Excuse me?

289
00:28:46.063 --> 00:28:48.232
Miss Hall and Ambrose
had a relationship

290
00:28:48.315 --> 00:28:49.566
which he took very seriously.

291
00:28:49.650 --> 00:28:52.653
She walked away, and he's been
wanting her back ever since.

292
00:28:52.736 --> 00:28:55.989
We believe she's our surest and
quickest way of locating him.

293
00:28:56.031 --> 00:28:57.532
And then what?

294
00:28:58.367 --> 00:29:00.452
Well, make sure
she continues to see him

295
00:29:00.494 --> 00:29:03.497
gets him to confide in her,
and report to you.

296
00:29:18.303 --> 00:29:20.973
You made it sound as if
I was recruiting her

297
00:29:21.014 --> 00:29:23.058
for her skills as a thief.

298
00:29:23.892 --> 00:29:27.271
Well, then I mislead you
or you made the wrong assumption.

299
00:29:27.354 --> 00:29:31.024
Either way, we are asking her
to resume a prior relationship

300
00:29:31.108 --> 00:29:33.443
not do anything she hasn't already done.

301
00:29:33.527 --> 00:29:35.529
Voluntarily, I might add.

302
00:29:38.073 --> 00:29:41.285
No, she's got no training
for this kind of thing.

303
00:29:41.868 --> 00:29:43.328
To go to bed with a man and lie to him?

304
00:29:43.370 --> 00:29:46.290
She's a woman.
She's got all the training she needs.

305
00:29:52.296 --> 00:29:54.881
I don't think I can get her to do it.

306
00:29:55.007 --> 00:29:57.050
- You mean it'll be difficult.
- Very.

307
00:29:57.134 --> 00:30:00.512
Well, this is not Mission: Difficult,
Mr. Hunt. It's Mission: Impossible.

308
00:30:00.554 --> 00:30:02.472
Difficult should be
a walk in the park for you.

309
00:30:02.556 --> 00:30:04.057
I'm open to suggestion.

310
00:30:04.099 --> 00:30:06.059
If you can think of a quicker way
to get to Ambrose

311
00:30:06.101 --> 00:30:07.311
you're welcome to try.

312
00:30:07.394 --> 00:30:08.729
You might want to take a look at these

313
00:30:08.770 --> 00:30:12.274
if you have any further qualms about
getting her to do the job.

314
00:31:10.290 --> 00:31:13.960
How many people are capable
of something like that?

315
00:31:17.923 --> 00:31:19.466
Sean Ambrose

316
00:31:19.841 --> 00:31:21.093
for one.

317
00:31:27.808 --> 00:31:28.975
Right.

318
00:31:39.653 --> 00:31:42.280
This wasn't what I had in mind, Nyah.

319
00:31:46.493 --> 00:31:48.995
But it is what you'd like me to do.

320
00:31:53.333 --> 00:31:54.376
What?

321
00:31:54.459 --> 00:31:57.337
Oh, let my conscience be my guide.
Is that it?

322
00:31:57.421 --> 00:31:58.505
Something like that.

323
00:31:58.588 --> 00:32:01.216
I don't have a conscience.
I'm a bloody thief.

324
00:32:05.554 --> 00:32:07.848
You're gonna try and force me
to do this?

325
00:32:07.889 --> 00:32:09.933
Generally, I don't favor
coercing someone

326
00:32:10.016 --> 00:32:13.437
not when there's a chance
my life could end up in their hands.

327
00:32:13.895 --> 00:32:15.605
Is that the only reason?

328
00:32:16.022 --> 00:32:18.316
- Can you think of a better one?
- Me? No.

329
00:32:18.358 --> 00:32:21.027
I was hoping you might, thinking that
somewhere in the course of business

330
00:32:21.111 --> 00:32:23.321
this got personal as well as physical!

331
00:32:23.363 --> 00:32:26.366
Okay. Would it make you feel any better
if I didn't want you to do this?

332
00:32:26.450 --> 00:32:28.702
- Yeah, much.
- Then feel better!

333
00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:09.367
Sean will never be anything
but suspicious if I pitch up

334
00:33:09.409 --> 00:33:11.745
saying, "Hey, honey, I'm home."

335
00:33:13.413 --> 00:33:15.207
What wouldn't make him suspicious?

336
00:33:15.248 --> 00:33:17.876
That I needed him in some urgent way.

337
00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:21.213
Destitute,

338
00:33:21.254 --> 00:33:23.006
in serious trouble,

339
00:33:23.089 --> 00:33:26.009
the kind
I couldn't possibly sort out myself.

340
00:33:26.927 --> 00:33:28.762
Serious trouble, Nyah

341
00:33:29.721 --> 00:33:32.140
is something I can always arrange.

342
00:33:36.144 --> 00:33:39.397
<i><font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> This transponder chip
is completely untraceable.</i>

343
00:33:40.857 --> 00:33:43.610
<i>It transmits your location to a satellite</i>

344
00:33:43.818 --> 00:33:46.530
<i>which can be read
by only this computer.</i>

345
00:33:47.113 --> 00:33:49.783
<i>We can then track you
to within three feet</i>

346
00:33:49.824 --> 00:33:50.951
<i>anywhere.</i>

347
00:33:53.787 --> 00:33:55.622
<i>Since your arrest,
I've been sending news bulletins</i>

348
00:33:55.664 --> 00:33:58.500
<i>to every law enforcement agency
in the world.</i>

349
00:33:58.583 --> 00:34:00.293
<i>I know Sean Ambrose</i>

350
00:34:01.294 --> 00:34:03.880
<i>and I guarantee
that after that airline crash</i>

351
00:34:04.464 --> 00:34:06.633
<i>he's monitoring every one of them.</i>

352
00:34:07.175 --> 00:34:08.802
<i>He knows you're there.</i>

353
00:34:10.428 --> 00:34:12.973
<i>And he has the means to get you out.</i>

354
00:34:15.642 --> 00:34:16.643
<i>Nyah.</i>

355
00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:20.981
<i>Nyah...</i>

356
00:34:22.816 --> 00:34:24.693
<i>I'm not gonna lose you.</i>

357
00:35:23.627 --> 00:35:24.878
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Agent Hunt?

358
00:35:24.961 --> 00:35:26.921
Good day, mate.
I'm William Baird, but Billy's okay.

359
00:35:27.005 --> 00:35:29.466
Anything you need me to get,
move or watch, I'm your man.

360
00:35:29.549 --> 00:35:31.217
I'll have a look around.

361
00:35:31.301 --> 00:35:32.302
<font color="#ff8000">[CHUCKLES]</font>

362
00:35:33.261 --> 00:35:34.262
<font color="#ff8000">[SQUISHING]</font>

363
00:35:36.014 --> 00:35:37.098
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Shit.

364
00:35:37.223 --> 00:35:38.558
Yes, it is.

365
00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.228
This ain't funny.

366
00:35:43.063 --> 00:35:45.940
I just bought these $800 Gucci shoes

367
00:35:46.024 --> 00:35:48.943
and you got me in a helicopter
with this man?

368
00:36:23.687 --> 00:36:25.814
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Computer's up. We got her.

369
00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:29.567
Let's put in the coordinates
and get a visual.

370
00:36:56.302 --> 00:37:00.181
- Visuals aren't coming up.
- Satellite doesn't work as fast as I do.

371
00:37:00.265 --> 00:37:02.559
Yeah, I heard about you, Luther.

372
00:37:02.642 --> 00:37:06.980
I wanna say it's an honor and a
pleasure to be working with you blokes.

373
00:37:10.775 --> 00:37:13.486
Isn't there any way
we can speed this up?

374
00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:17.031
With what? This is the only computer
that will do this.

375
00:38:15.548 --> 00:38:17.217
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Ethan, here we go.

376
00:38:28.019 --> 00:38:31.523
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Now there's a bloke who knows
how to give a proper welcome.

377
00:38:33.233 --> 00:38:36.653
Don't get me wrong, mate.
You were very friendly also.

378
00:38:38.238 --> 00:38:39.531
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Is it him then?

379
00:38:39.697 --> 00:38:41.449
- It's him, Billy.
- So we got him.

380
00:38:41.533 --> 00:38:43.409
We don't know what we've got.

381
00:38:43.451 --> 00:38:45.578
'Cause we don't know what he's got

382
00:38:45.620 --> 00:38:48.873
where he's got it
or what he's doing in Sydney with it.

383
00:38:56.256 --> 00:38:57.924
Not much luggage.

384
00:38:58.341 --> 00:39:00.218
I left in a bit of a hurry.

385
00:39:00.510 --> 00:39:02.762
I'm incredibly grateful, Sean.

386
00:39:03.763 --> 00:39:06.182
How in the world did you find me?

387
00:39:07.976 --> 00:39:10.144
How I usually find you.

388
00:39:11.437 --> 00:39:12.772
Magic.

389
00:39:28.788 --> 00:39:29.789
<font color="#ff8000">[HUMMING]</font>

390
00:39:31.833 --> 00:39:33.209
No flies on her.

391
00:39:33.668 --> 00:39:37.422
No bugs either. No transmissions.
She's clean.

392
00:39:38.464 --> 00:39:39.924
All cats are.

393
00:39:47.974 --> 00:39:49.309
Your room?

394
00:39:53.855 --> 00:39:55.273
And my room?

395
00:40:12.665 --> 00:40:13.917
She did it.

396
00:40:14.834 --> 00:40:16.502
She's in the compound.

397
00:40:17.420 --> 00:40:18.504
Yeah?

398
00:40:19.672 --> 00:40:23.176
We've just rolled up a snowball
and tossed it into hell.

399
00:40:23.843 --> 00:40:26.262
Now we'll see what chance it has.

400
00:40:28.222 --> 00:40:29.557
Try it on.

401
00:40:33.519 --> 00:40:34.771
Go ahead.

402
00:40:42.028 --> 00:40:44.864
I'm dying to see
if I remembered your size.

403
00:41:14.394 --> 00:41:17.313
You're not interested
in seeing how it looks?

404
00:41:18.314 --> 00:41:19.607
Oh, I am.

405
00:41:22.902 --> 00:41:24.070
Later.

406
00:41:47.844 --> 00:41:50.013
<i><font color="#ffff80">NEKHORVICH:</font> Every search for a hero</i>

407
00:41:50.096 --> 00:41:53.433
<i>must begin with something
that every hero requires,</i>

408
00:41:53.516 --> 00:41:54.851
<i>a villain.</i>

409
00:41:55.435 --> 00:41:59.647
<i>Therefore
in a search for our hero, Bellerophon</i>

410
00:42:00.440 --> 00:42:02.608
<i>we created a monster</i>

411
00:42:02.984 --> 00:42:04.235
<i>Chimera.</i>

412
00:42:04.402 --> 00:42:06.487
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font>
Nekhorvich was a molecular biologist.

413
00:42:06.571 --> 00:42:09.407
Why is he going on
about an old Greek myth?

414
00:42:09.532 --> 00:42:12.827
Nekhorvich specialized in
recombining DNA molecules.

415
00:42:14.662 --> 00:42:16.039
In the myth

416
00:42:16.456 --> 00:42:19.500
Bellerophon was a prince
who killed the Chimera,

417
00:42:20.793 --> 00:42:23.254
a monster with the head of a lion

418
00:42:23.963 --> 00:42:26.382
and the tail of a serpent

419
00:42:27.216 --> 00:42:29.469
who plagued the ancient world.

420
00:42:30.595 --> 00:42:33.973
I think Nekhorvich created
a monster virus in Chimera

421
00:42:34.766 --> 00:42:36.809
and the antivirus to kill it

422
00:42:36.851 --> 00:42:38.644
in Bellerophon.

423
00:42:40.104 --> 00:42:41.731
That simple, huh?

424
00:42:44.067 --> 00:42:45.318
Why not?

425
00:43:00.666 --> 00:43:01.667
<font color="#ff8000">[AMBROSE SNICKERS]</font>

426
00:43:03.711 --> 00:43:05.838
Thirty-seven million pounds.

427
00:43:07.131 --> 00:43:10.009
Well, that's a promising bid
for Nekhorvich's work.

428
00:43:12.136 --> 00:43:15.681
Don't look so worried, Hugh.
We're halfway there.

429
00:43:19.143 --> 00:43:21.270
We'll need this at the track

430
00:43:22.897 --> 00:43:25.191
if we're going to get the other half.

431
00:43:34.617 --> 00:43:35.993
Well, then...

432
00:43:37.829 --> 00:43:39.038
Sorted.

433
00:43:45.586 --> 00:43:47.130
Not everything.

434
00:43:49.549 --> 00:43:51.717
Why do you think she's really here?

435
00:43:54.220 --> 00:43:56.222
From her point of view or mine?

436
00:43:56.556 --> 00:43:58.724
She wasn't exactly gagging for it

437
00:43:58.808 --> 00:44:01.227
when she left you six months ago.

438
00:44:04.188 --> 00:44:06.732
The question is, "Do you trust her?"

439
00:44:15.074 --> 00:44:17.368
One considers her timing, of course.

440
00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:20.496
Getting nicked within a week
of the plane going down.

441
00:44:20.580 --> 00:44:21.914
Suggestive

442
00:44:22.790 --> 00:44:24.834
even borderline suspicious

443
00:44:25.918 --> 00:44:27.795
but hardly conclusive.

444
00:44:33.926 --> 00:44:36.470
You've thought about it at any rate.

445
00:44:41.475 --> 00:44:42.977
Tell me, Hugh.

446
00:44:43.769 --> 00:44:48.024
You don't exactly hang on
Nyah's every word and gesture, do you?

447
00:44:51.652 --> 00:44:53.613
That's a fairly ratty nail.

448
00:44:59.243 --> 00:45:00.453
Please.

449
00:45:00.536 --> 00:45:04.624
Suppose she is some sort of Trojan
horse sent in by IMF

450
00:45:04.665 --> 00:45:06.000
to spy on us?

451
00:45:06.083 --> 00:45:09.837
Why should I deny myself the pleasure
of a ride or two?

452
00:45:09.962 --> 00:45:10.963
<font color="#ff8000">[HUGH SCREAMING]</font>

453
00:45:11.464 --> 00:45:14.926
Or don't you think I can learn more
from her than she can from me?

454
00:45:14.967 --> 00:45:18.012
I do! I do! I do!

455
00:45:19.889 --> 00:45:22.767
Now, Hugh, you must realize

456
00:45:22.892 --> 00:45:26.520
that some of us
have the burden of sex to deal with.

457
00:45:26.771 --> 00:45:29.982
And I may or may not know
why she thinks she's here

458
00:45:30.149 --> 00:45:32.151
but I'm willing to take the risk

459
00:45:32.193 --> 00:45:33.819
because, Hugh

460
00:45:34.820 --> 00:45:35.821
<font color="#ff8000">[HUGH TREMBLING]</font>

461
00:45:35.905 --> 00:45:37.990
I am gagging for it.

462
00:45:38.157 --> 00:45:39.158
<font color="#ff8000">[SCREAMING]</font>

463
00:45:47.792 --> 00:45:48.793
<font color="#ff8000">[CROWD CHEERING]</font>

464
00:45:52.046 --> 00:45:53.464
<i><font color="#ff8000">[ANNOUNCER
TALKING INDISTINCTLY]</font></i>

465
00:46:01.013 --> 00:46:04.058
Come on! Come on!

466
00:46:04.725 --> 00:46:05.768
<font color="#ff8000">[NYAH SQUEALING]</font>

467
00:46:05.851 --> 00:46:08.646
Darling, you won!

468
00:46:08.813 --> 00:46:10.398
I suppose I did.

469
00:46:10.564 --> 00:46:12.441
What made you pick that nag?

470
00:46:12.525 --> 00:46:14.527
She's never won a bloody thing.

471
00:46:14.610 --> 00:46:15.778
"Thief in the Night."

472
00:46:15.861 --> 00:46:16.862
<font color="#ff8000">[LAUGHING]</font>

473
00:46:16.946 --> 00:46:18.531
Say no more.

474
00:46:21.534 --> 00:46:23.411
I'm off to grab a drink.

475
00:46:23.494 --> 00:46:25.705
- You still favor the Bellinis?
- Hmm.

476
00:46:26.872 --> 00:46:27.873
<font color="#ff8000">[PEOPLE CHATTERING]</font>

477
00:46:42.888 --> 00:46:44.432
<font color="#ffff80">MAN:</font> Naturally Vain.

478
00:46:46.267 --> 00:46:47.601
Pardon me?

479
00:46:47.685 --> 00:46:49.228
Naturally Vain?

480
00:46:50.771 --> 00:46:54.108
In the fourth. Check her out. She's due.

481
00:47:07.872 --> 00:47:10.791
<i><font color="#ffff80">ETHAN ON EARPIECE:</font> You can speak
as if I'm right by your side.</i>

482
00:47:10.875 --> 00:47:13.044
Where are you?

483
00:47:13.085 --> 00:47:15.796
<i>Mounting enclosure,
just off the track, 2:00.</i>

484
00:47:31.103 --> 00:47:32.646
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> How's it going?

485
00:47:33.606 --> 00:47:35.358
Just like old times.

486
00:47:37.109 --> 00:47:38.861
Just like old times?

487
00:47:39.862 --> 00:47:41.238
Just about.

488
00:47:44.116 --> 00:47:46.869
Tell me who you've run into
at Ambrose's.

489
00:47:47.411 --> 00:47:51.665
Near as I can tell, there's about a
half dozen blokes about the place.

490
00:47:51.749 --> 00:47:53.000
<i><font color="#ffff80">NYAH:</font> Maybe more.</i>

491
00:47:53.084 --> 00:47:55.127
Hugh Stamp. Old friend of Sean's.

492
00:47:55.211 --> 00:47:57.296
He's the only one I recognize.

493
00:47:57.338 --> 00:47:59.215
A creep and then some.

494
00:47:59.382 --> 00:48:03.052
We know him. He's over your
left shoulder looking at you right now.

495
00:48:04.804 --> 00:48:08.641
Ambrose has photos of newspapers
with money piled on them.

496
00:48:08.808 --> 00:48:11.102
Thirty-seven million
on the <i>London Times.</i>

497
00:48:11.143 --> 00:48:12.812
What's that about?

498
00:48:14.688 --> 00:48:16.899
Bids from possible Chimera buyers.

499
00:48:27.743 --> 00:48:30.538
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Ambrose is meeting some bloke
in the bar.

500
00:48:30.621 --> 00:48:34.291
<i><font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Big bloke. Ginger hair.
They're into something.</i>

501
00:48:40.881 --> 00:48:43.509
- <font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Who is this guy?
- Checking now, Ethan.

502
00:48:50.850 --> 00:48:54.270
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> John McCloy,
CEO Biocyte Pharmaceuticals,

503
00:48:54.353 --> 00:48:57.356
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> 1989, acquired Biocyte
in a hostile takeover.</i>

504
00:48:59.984 --> 00:49:02.111
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> He was Nekhorvich's boss.
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Right.

505
00:49:02.194 --> 00:49:05.239
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> He worked for him
as the research scientist at Biocyte.</i>

506
00:49:06.574 --> 00:49:09.869
<i>Ambrose is showing something
to McCloy on a digital camera.</i>

507
00:49:10.578 --> 00:49:14.039
Whatever McCloy's looking at,
he's not happy about it.

508
00:49:24.675 --> 00:49:26.969
<i>Ambrose just pulled the camera's
memory card</i>

509
00:49:27.052 --> 00:49:28.888
<i>and put it into an envelope.</i>

510
00:49:30.848 --> 00:49:33.058
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font>
Put it in his inner left jacket pocket.</i>

511
00:49:33.100 --> 00:49:35.227
<i>Confirm left jacket pocket.</i>

512
00:49:36.562 --> 00:49:37.938
Roger that.

513
00:49:40.774 --> 00:49:41.859
Nyah,

514
00:49:42.568 --> 00:49:44.487
<i>Ambrose is on his way back to you.</i>

515
00:49:44.570 --> 00:49:47.865
- There's an envelope inside...
- His left jacket pocket.

516
00:49:48.574 --> 00:49:49.867
That's right.

517
00:49:49.909 --> 00:49:51.202
Where do I meet you?

518
00:49:51.243 --> 00:49:53.579
<i>Betting table 12, off the paddock.</i>

519
00:49:53.662 --> 00:49:57.082
- Are you sure you're up to this?
- I'll muddle through.

520
00:49:58.417 --> 00:50:00.920
- There you are.
- See anything you like?

521
00:50:00.961 --> 00:50:02.922
Well, yeah.

522
00:50:03.005 --> 00:50:04.673
Naturally Vain.

523
00:50:04.757 --> 00:50:06.258
But they're about to close the betting

524
00:50:06.342 --> 00:50:08.385
- and I haven't a bean.
- Nyah!

525
00:50:08.719 --> 00:50:11.347
- Would you mind terribly?
- Not at all.

526
00:50:11.430 --> 00:50:14.099
But you are gonna pay for it

527
00:50:14.642 --> 00:50:16.310
and with interest.

528
00:50:16.977 --> 00:50:18.604
I have no doubt.

529
00:50:19.772 --> 00:50:21.148
Hold on.

530
00:50:34.995 --> 00:50:37.122
Put down a thousand for me.

531
00:50:41.460 --> 00:50:43.671
- To win?
- What else?

532
00:50:47.174 --> 00:50:49.009
Billy, make sure Nyah's not followed.

533
00:50:49.093 --> 00:50:50.803
No worries, mate.

534
00:50:50.844 --> 00:50:53.681
Luther, digital camera,
ready to transmit.

535
00:50:53.764 --> 00:50:55.224
<i><font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Betting table 12.</i>

536
00:51:10.155 --> 00:51:12.241
- There you go.
- Thanks.

537
00:51:12.324 --> 00:51:13.325
<font color="#ff8000">[GROANING]</font>

538
00:51:14.785 --> 00:51:17.162
Sorry about that, mate.
That must have...

539
00:51:18.247 --> 00:51:19.623
Say again?

540
00:51:19.665 --> 00:51:20.708
<font color="#ff8000">[MUTTERING]</font>

541
00:51:20.791 --> 00:51:23.919
Whatever you're about,
in future watch your step.

542
00:51:24.003 --> 00:51:26.714
Never know who you might run into.

543
00:51:28.299 --> 00:51:29.967
Where's the loo?

544
00:51:31.510 --> 00:51:32.761
Thanks, mate.

545
00:51:32.845 --> 00:51:33.846
<font color="#ff8000">[GASPING]</font>

546
00:51:38.726 --> 00:51:40.019
<font color="#ff8000">[CROWD CHATTERING]</font>

547
00:51:56.702 --> 00:51:58.203
How'd you do?

548
00:51:58.662 --> 00:52:00.331
Don't turn around.

549
00:52:01.373 --> 00:52:02.708
I managed.

550
00:52:09.214 --> 00:52:10.591
You turned around.

551
00:52:11.300 --> 00:52:13.719
What are you gonna do, spank me?

552
00:52:18.015 --> 00:52:19.016
<font color="#ff8000">[LUTHER CLEARING THROAT]</font>

553
00:52:39.411 --> 00:52:41.497
I'm booted up. Go, Ethan.

554
00:52:48.629 --> 00:52:50.172
Are you getting this?

555
00:53:01.433 --> 00:53:03.602
"Sergei Gradski"

556
00:53:04.853 --> 00:53:07.106
"20 hours after exposure."

557
00:53:46.270 --> 00:53:47.312
God.

558
00:53:56.113 --> 00:53:57.573
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Stamp's out of the loo.

559
00:53:57.656 --> 00:54:00.659
<i><font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> He's coming out of the tunnel
heading your way, mate.</i>

560
00:54:00.826 --> 00:54:03.328
- I want you out of Ambrose's place.
- What are you talking about?

561
00:54:03.370 --> 00:54:05.664
What's happened? What did you see?

562
00:54:09.585 --> 00:54:12.212
<i>Okay, he's coming up
behind you, Ethan.</i>

563
00:54:12.296 --> 00:54:15.632
You've done your job.
I want you out of Australia.

564
00:54:15.674 --> 00:54:18.260
- Thirty steps.
- How do you suggest I go about it?

565
00:54:18.343 --> 00:54:20.012
- <font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Twenty, nineteen...
- He's touched your heart,

566
00:54:20.095 --> 00:54:21.680
you're overwhelmed
and need to think it over.

567
00:54:21.764 --> 00:54:23.557
Fifteen, fourteen.

568
00:54:23.640 --> 00:54:25.517
- Twelve, eleven.
- I want you out of there now.

569
00:54:25.601 --> 00:54:27.186
Give me the earpiece.

570
00:54:27.311 --> 00:54:28.771
Nine, Ethan. Eight.

571
00:54:28.854 --> 00:54:32.399
If you don't get out of there,
I'm coming in and getting you out.

572
00:54:32.483 --> 00:54:34.318
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Get out of there.

573
00:54:36.612 --> 00:54:38.655
You place your bet, ma'am?

574
00:54:41.200 --> 00:54:42.284
Just

575
00:54:45.370 --> 00:54:47.372
<i><font color="#ffff80">MALE ANNOUNCER:</font>
Horses are ready to race.</i>

576
00:54:47.414 --> 00:54:48.415
<font color="#ff8000">[STARTER BELL RINGS]</font>

577
00:54:56.507 --> 00:54:57.591
Come on!

578
00:54:57.674 --> 00:55:00.719
Come on! Your nag's making a run
for it on the outside.

579
00:55:03.847 --> 00:55:05.098
Come on!

580
00:55:09.770 --> 00:55:12.064
You picked another winner!

581
00:55:18.904 --> 00:55:21.073
I thought you were going to dinner.

582
00:55:22.199 --> 00:55:25.577
Hugh, take care
of the Nekhorvich memory card.

583
00:55:27.454 --> 00:55:28.872
Where is it?

584
00:55:29.331 --> 00:55:31.875
In the envelope in my jacket pocket.

585
00:55:34.753 --> 00:55:37.339
My right jacket pocket.

586
00:55:39.925 --> 00:55:42.761
<i>We at our state-of—the-art,
solar-powered Biocyte building</i>

587
00:55:42.803 --> 00:55:45.764
<i>recognize that eternal vigilance
is the price of health</i>

588
00:55:45.848 --> 00:55:47.516
<i>whether it's funding the teaching center</i>

589
00:55:47.599 --> 00:55:49.101
<i>at the Royal Prince Edward Hospital,</i>

590
00:55:49.184 --> 00:55:51.478
<i>removing aerosol products
from the market</i>

591
00:55:51.562 --> 00:55:55.232
<i>or braving the influenza quarantine
at Bruny Island late last month.</i>

592
00:55:55.274 --> 00:55:56.692
<i>At Biocyte,</i>

593
00:55:56.775 --> 00:55:59.444
<i>your life is our life's work.</i>

594
00:56:01.530 --> 00:56:03.782
We've got an opportunity here.

595
00:56:04.449 --> 00:56:06.451
I'm not going to miss it.

596
00:56:37.316 --> 00:56:39.109
<font color="#ffff80">McCLOY:</font> George, take me home.

597
00:56:56.668 --> 00:56:57.961
George.

598
00:57:01.673 --> 00:57:02.674
George.

599
00:57:12.225 --> 00:57:14.770
What the hell?

600
00:57:18.231 --> 00:57:19.232
<i>George!</i>

601
00:57:27.199 --> 00:57:28.533
<i>George. George!</i>

602
00:57:28.992 --> 00:57:31.078
<font color="#ff8000">[COUGHING]</font>

603
00:57:31.620 --> 00:57:33.205
<font color="#ff8000">[GASPING AND CHOKING]</font>

604
00:57:36.375 --> 00:57:37.668
<font color="#ffff80">NYAH:</font> Sean?

605
00:57:42.172 --> 00:57:43.173
Sean.

606
00:57:54.726 --> 00:57:55.936
<font color="#ff8000">[MEN CHATTERING]</font>

607
00:57:58.105 --> 00:57:59.398
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN LAUGHING]</font>

608
00:58:21.003 --> 00:58:22.045
<font color="#ff8000">[GASPS]</font>

609
00:58:22.087 --> 00:58:23.588
<font color="#ffff80">MAN:</font> Shh. Shh. Shh.

610
00:58:25.924 --> 00:58:27.050
Easy.

611
00:58:28.260 --> 00:58:29.594
Oh, Ethan.

612
00:58:29.803 --> 00:58:31.263
Are you okay?

613
00:58:31.638 --> 00:58:33.181
Yeah, I am now.

614
00:58:33.765 --> 00:58:34.766
<font color="#ff8000">[SIGHS]</font>

615
00:58:53.452 --> 00:58:54.453
<font color="#ff8000">[GURGLING]</font>

616
00:59:08.592 --> 00:59:10.135
<font color="#ff8000">[WHEEZING]</font>

617
00:59:20.395 --> 00:59:21.688
<font color="#ffff80">MCCLOY:</font> What is this?

618
00:59:22.230 --> 00:59:24.232
A visit from an old friend.

619
00:59:24.357 --> 00:59:25.734
<font color="#ff8000">[PANTING]</font>

620
00:59:26.276 --> 00:59:28.945
You crashed on the plane. You're dead.

621
00:59:29.362 --> 00:59:30.989
Tired, certainly.

622
00:59:31.073 --> 00:59:33.617
But dead is a little extreme.

623
00:59:35.160 --> 00:59:36.328
On the other hand

624
00:59:36.411 --> 00:59:40.457
when my colleague Gradski had
your pulse and your blood pressure

625
00:59:41.625 --> 00:59:43.919
he had less than a day to live.

626
00:59:48.215 --> 00:59:50.884
You're infected with Chimera, my friend.

627
00:59:54.262 --> 00:59:56.014
No use, my friend.

628
00:59:57.015 --> 00:59:58.433
The medical staff

629
00:59:58.517 --> 01:00:00.310
wants no part of this.

630
01:00:00.769 --> 01:00:04.356
Doctors don't fancy the idea of dying
any more than anybody else.

631
01:00:04.856 --> 01:00:06.608
How could I possibly be infected?

632
01:00:06.691 --> 01:00:11.279
That's exactly what Gradski said
27 hours before he died.

633
01:00:12.656 --> 01:00:15.283
You've got the antidote,
you miserable bastard!

634
01:00:15.367 --> 01:00:17.869
- You stole Bellerophon. All of it!
- My, my, my.

635
01:00:17.911 --> 01:00:18.912
I need it.

636
01:00:18.995 --> 01:00:21.706
I need it now,
you whacked-out Russian gypsy!

637
01:00:21.790 --> 01:00:26.628
And what about Gradski, who you
deliberately infected with Chimera?

638
01:00:26.711 --> 01:00:31.049
How was I to know he needed treatment
with Bellerophon within 20 hours?

639
01:00:31.174 --> 01:00:32.592
By asking me.

640
01:00:32.676 --> 01:00:34.970
You still don't get it, do you?

641
01:00:35.220 --> 01:00:38.890
I needed to know just how bad
the disease was in the real world

642
01:00:38.974 --> 01:00:40.600
not just the lab.

643
01:00:40.892 --> 01:00:44.104
You were genetically splicing together
strains of influenza

644
01:00:44.187 --> 01:00:46.690
to create a cure for all influenzas.

645
01:00:46.731 --> 01:00:50.443
But you were also creating
a disease so terrible in Chimera

646
01:00:51.027 --> 01:00:53.155
the cure would be priceless.

647
01:00:53.238 --> 01:00:56.241
I needed Chimera
in order to peddle Bellerophon.

648
01:00:56.324 --> 01:00:59.077
It's not that difficult to understand, is it?

649
01:00:59.494 --> 01:01:02.747
Look, I've got the virus,
you've got the cure.

650
01:01:02.831 --> 01:01:04.457
I need them both.

651
01:01:04.833 --> 01:01:09.045
Time was, a shot of penicillin
would knock off every bug in the zoo.

652
01:01:09.171 --> 01:01:10.589
Not anymore.

653
01:01:11.256 --> 01:01:15.135
If I couldn't make money killing
the microscopic little shits out there

654
01:01:15.427 --> 01:01:18.930
you'd help me put one out there
that I could make money on.

655
01:01:19.014 --> 01:01:22.225
Well, there it is. I've confessed.

656
01:01:23.059 --> 01:01:25.562
I, John C. McCloy

657
01:01:25.770 --> 01:01:29.399
am in business to make money.

658
01:01:30.525 --> 01:01:34.487
Now forget any deal you may have made
with that thug Ambrose

659
01:01:34.905 --> 01:01:37.699
get me treated,
and let's go back to work.

660
01:01:38.325 --> 01:01:39.576
You know

661
01:01:40.452 --> 01:01:44.122
I think it's a little late for that.

662
01:01:45.498 --> 01:01:47.709
Do give my regards to Gradski

663
01:01:48.877 --> 01:01:50.420
if you see him.

664
01:02:01.306 --> 01:02:02.807
Well?

665
01:02:06.519 --> 01:02:08.188
I've heard

666
01:02:11.942 --> 01:02:13.652
all I need to hear.

667
01:02:16.696 --> 01:02:17.906
Nyah.

668
01:02:19.741 --> 01:02:24.663
It's imperative that we do nothing
to alarm Ambrose.

669
01:02:25.622 --> 01:02:26.706
What?

670
01:02:28.083 --> 01:02:29.709
You told me to leave as soon as I could.

671
01:02:29.793 --> 01:02:31.586
I thought you were here to collect me!

672
01:02:31.711 --> 01:02:32.712
<font color="#ff8000">[SHUSHING]</font>

673
01:02:34.297 --> 01:02:36.758
Listen to me. There's no time to talk.

674
01:02:38.176 --> 01:02:39.594
It is critical,

675
01:02:39.678 --> 01:02:42.305
absolutely critical

676
01:02:43.181 --> 01:02:46.351
that you do whatever Ambrose asks.

677
01:02:49.771 --> 01:02:51.731
Do you understand me?

678
01:02:54.943 --> 01:02:56.194
Don't worry.

679
01:02:58.446 --> 01:03:00.198
It Will all be over

680
01:03:00.949 --> 01:03:02.284
very soon.

681
01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:11.459
That's a promise.

682
01:03:12.711 --> 01:03:14.045
Come on.

683
01:03:17.382 --> 01:03:18.717
Off you go.

684
01:03:49.873 --> 01:03:51.458
Luther, we know this much.

685
01:03:51.541 --> 01:03:55.253
Nekhorvich gets on a plane to go to the
Center for Disease Control in Atlanta.

686
01:03:55.420 --> 01:03:58.173
He's carrying a virus he created,
Chimera,

687
01:03:58.631 --> 01:04:01.593
and the cure for that virus, Bellerophon.

688
01:04:05.138 --> 01:04:06.848
Ambrose doesn't have the virus.

689
01:04:07.015 --> 01:04:09.225
That's why Ambrose needs McCloy.

690
01:04:10.852 --> 01:04:13.772
So we go into Biocyte, kill Chimera

691
01:04:15.190 --> 01:04:19.277
Ambrose has a cure without a disease
and we're home free.

692
01:04:20.653 --> 01:04:21.946
<i><font color="#ffff80">HUGH:</font> You were right.</i>

693
01:04:22.030 --> 01:04:24.407
Hunt stung McCloy tonight.

694
01:04:25.450 --> 01:04:27.077
So he knows.

695
01:04:27.577 --> 01:04:29.704
He'll be going into Biocyte.

696
01:04:31.456 --> 01:04:32.624
Good.

697
01:04:33.458 --> 01:04:35.919
Then we know where he'll be, don't we?

698
01:04:38.296 --> 01:04:39.756
Well done, Hugh.

699
01:04:41.758 --> 01:04:43.134
Well done.

700
01:04:51.017 --> 01:04:52.644
<font color="#ff8000">[CAR HORN HONKING]</font>

701
01:04:53.144 --> 01:04:54.145
<font color="#ff8000">[BILLY SHOUTING]</font>

702
01:04:55.480 --> 01:04:57.607
You're home, mate. Home.

703
01:04:59.442 --> 01:05:00.443
<font color="#ff8000">[CLEARING THROAT]</font>

704
01:05:01.486 --> 01:05:04.823
Where's George, my regular driver?
Where is he?

705
01:05:04.906 --> 01:05:07.534
He's gone home sick. Touch of the flu.

706
01:05:10.495 --> 01:05:11.996
The building up and running yet?

707
01:05:16.793 --> 01:05:20.505
- That's not exactly it.
- Sorry, but this is a Biocyte facility.

708
01:05:20.547 --> 01:05:22.215
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Their storage structure.

709
01:05:22.340 --> 01:05:23.716
I'll have it up in a minute.

710
01:05:26.052 --> 01:05:28.346
Okay, take a look at this.

711
01:05:28.638 --> 01:05:29.973
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Let's start from the inside out.

712
01:05:30.014 --> 01:05:33.101
All storage and production of Chimera
is done here

713
01:05:33.184 --> 01:05:35.603
in this lab on the 42nd floor.

714
01:05:36.354 --> 01:05:38.815
Hunt's target will be the Chimera

715
01:05:38.857 --> 01:05:42.861
stored and manufactured at Biocyte
on the 42nd floor.

716
01:05:44.279 --> 01:05:48.366
If you look at Hunt's operational history,
and I have,

717
01:05:48.700 --> 01:05:52.412
he invariably favors misdirection
over confrontation.

718
01:05:53.246 --> 01:05:55.498
<i><font color="#ffff80">AMBROSE:</font> He'll never
break into Biocyte from the bottom,</i>

719
01:05:55.540 --> 01:05:57.292
<i>where security is heaviest.</i>

720
01:05:57.917 --> 01:05:59.586
No garage entrances.

721
01:05:59.752 --> 01:06:03.047
Lobby's protected by five guards
on rotating patrol.

722
01:06:04.841 --> 01:06:08.094
Not going in from the ground.
Show me the atrium.

723
01:06:09.095 --> 01:06:11.890
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> The atrium? One of a kind.

724
01:06:12.390 --> 01:06:14.517
Runs down through
the center of the building.

725
01:06:14.559 --> 01:06:18.730
Provides 24-hour natural light
via mirrors and daylight storage cells,

726
01:06:18.771 --> 01:06:21.191
<i>optimum growing conditions
for the virus.</i>

727
01:06:21.232 --> 01:06:24.944
<i>Ends in a glass floor
which doubles as part of the lab ceiling.</i>

728
01:06:28.281 --> 01:06:29.574
Uh-uh.

729
01:06:29.866 --> 01:06:32.285
The atrium roof closes at sundown.

730
01:06:32.410 --> 01:06:35.580
And if the louvers are up
for more than 40 seconds at night,

731
01:06:35.663 --> 01:06:39.417
the civil emergency alarms are tripped.
Those even I can't stop.

732
01:06:40.502 --> 01:06:44.589
We have a total of 40 seconds
to get you in and the cables out.

733
01:06:47.258 --> 01:06:52.180
Hunt will prefer to enter Biocyte
from the top, where security is minimal.

734
01:06:52.597 --> 01:06:56.100
He'll undoubtedly engage
in some aerobatic insanity

735
01:06:56.184 --> 01:06:59.437
before he'll risk harming a hair
on a security guard's head.

736
01:07:14.077 --> 01:07:16.621
- Check, check. Copy?
- You're five-by-five.

737
01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:22.835
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Luther, how we doing?

738
01:07:23.169 --> 01:07:25.421
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Not there yet, Ethan.
I'll give you the word.

739
01:07:28.716 --> 01:07:30.635
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Billy, ready to go?

740
01:07:35.598 --> 01:07:38.476
- Package away in five.
- Not yet. The louvers aren't moving.

741
01:07:38.977 --> 01:07:40.311
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Luther, we gotta go.

742
01:07:40.353 --> 01:07:42.522
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Wait.
There's a glitch in the access code.</i>

743
01:07:52.407 --> 01:07:55.326
<i><font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Luther, we're out of time.
On the count.</i>

744
01:07:55.410 --> 01:07:58.329
Please, baby, open up. Open up.

745
01:07:58.413 --> 01:08:00.748
Five, four...

746
01:08:00.957 --> 01:08:03.835
- Come on!
- ...three, two, one!

747
01:08:03.876 --> 01:08:06.379
- I'm going now!
- Ethan, wait!

748
01:08:19.851 --> 01:08:20.852
<font color="#ff8000">[LAUGHING]</font>

749
01:08:42.582 --> 01:08:45.960
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> 25, 24, 23,</i>

750
01:08:46.586 --> 01:08:50.048
22, 21, 20.

751
01:08:51.382 --> 01:08:54.218
You've got 19 seconds
to clear the cable.

752
01:09:02.226 --> 01:09:04.228
Okay, retracting cable.

753
01:09:05.313 --> 01:09:06.564
<font color="#ff8000">[TIMER BEEPING]</font>

754
01:09:09.359 --> 01:09:10.735
Come on.

755
01:09:11.653 --> 01:09:15.907
Nine, eight, seven, six, five,

756
01:09:16.199 --> 01:09:19.077
<i>four, three, two...</i>

757
01:09:20.870 --> 01:09:22.664
Cable's clear!

758
01:09:36.427 --> 01:09:38.054
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Transponder activated.

759
01:09:38.096 --> 01:09:40.431
Reading package and cable clear.

760
01:09:49.107 --> 01:09:51.401
He'll breach the lab
at the only possible time.

761
01:09:51.442 --> 01:09:53.820
Whether you break in from the ground
or the roof,

762
01:09:54.278 --> 01:09:57.240
it's 23:00 hours, one minute

763
01:09:57.281 --> 01:10:00.827
when the air filtration generators
will cover the sound of Hunt's break-in

764
01:10:00.910 --> 01:10:05.123
and rotating guards make the building
vulnerable to our break-in from below.

765
01:10:07.583 --> 01:10:09.961
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Ethan, the generators
are about to go active.</i>

766
01:10:10.002 --> 01:10:13.172
Just a friendly reminder,
we'll be out of contact for eight minutes.

767
01:10:45.663 --> 01:10:48.416
<i><font color="#ffff80">AMBROSE:</font>
I'm betting Hunt will destroy Chimera</i>

768
01:10:48.499 --> 01:10:51.294
rather than attempt to preserve
any part of it.

769
01:10:51.878 --> 01:10:54.046
He'll have to do it in two places.

770
01:10:54.839 --> 01:10:56.007
First,

771
01:10:56.883 --> 01:10:59.761
the incubation room
where the growth vials are kept.

772
01:11:02.263 --> 01:11:05.099
<i>And finally, in the inoculation chamber</i>

773
01:11:05.183 --> 01:11:09.020
<i>holding the last remaining
Chimera virus and three injection guns.</i>

774
01:11:11.272 --> 01:11:14.817
He won't be allowed to destroy the virus
in those guns.

775
01:11:18.696 --> 01:11:20.198
<font color="#ff8000">[BEEPING]</font>

776
01:11:30.666 --> 01:11:32.960
What's this? You're on time for once?

777
01:11:33.211 --> 01:11:34.879
Not exactly, sport.

778
01:11:35.713 --> 01:11:37.048
<font color="#ff8000">[GUNSHOTS]</font>

779
01:11:37.131 --> 01:11:38.132
<font color="#ff8000">[BODY FALLING]</font>

780
01:11:41.093 --> 01:11:42.136
<font color="#ff8000">[RECORDER BEEPS]</font>

781
01:11:42.220 --> 01:11:44.055
<i>John C. McCloy.</i>

782
01:11:59.695 --> 01:12:01.072
<font color="#ff8000">[BEEPING]</font>

783
01:12:05.243 --> 01:12:06.994
Billy, we've got a problem.

784
01:12:07.161 --> 01:12:10.665
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Nyah's on the wing up early.
Billy, do you copy?</i>

785
01:12:10.748 --> 01:12:14.001
Yeah, I got you, Luther.
Exactly where is she?

786
01:12:14.085 --> 01:12:16.504
- In the building.
<i>- Say again, mate.</i>

787
01:12:17.213 --> 01:12:19.131
Sounds like you said
she's in the building.

788
01:12:19.215 --> 01:12:20.633
I am. She is.

789
01:12:22.301 --> 01:12:25.721
Well, then, she's not likely
to be alone, is she?

790
01:12:25.972 --> 01:12:28.474
<font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> She's in the elevator
headed towards Ethan.

791
01:12:28.599 --> 01:12:30.268
The question is, how many of them?

792
01:12:30.351 --> 01:12:33.229
I can't get through to Ethan
till the generators go off.

793
01:12:33.396 --> 01:12:34.397
When's that?

794
01:12:34.438 --> 01:12:37.275
Not for another five-and-a-half minutes.

795
01:13:13.269 --> 01:13:15.313
<i><font color="#ffff80">COMPUTER:</font> Chimera in vitro pH</i>

796
01:13:15.396 --> 01:13:18.900
<i>and temperature level
outside optimal range.</i>

797
01:13:19.567 --> 01:13:21.485
<i>Chimera in vitro pH</i>

798
01:13:21.527 --> 01:13:25.197
<i>and temperature level
outside optimal range.</i>

799
01:13:25.364 --> 01:13:29.660
<i>Chimera working seed stock pH
at critical level.</i>

800
01:13:29.994 --> 01:13:33.664
<i>Alert. Chimera stock life threatened.</i>

801
01:13:34.165 --> 01:13:37.710
<i>Alert. Chimera stock life terminated.</i>

802
01:13:42.965 --> 01:13:45.676
Come on, Ethan. Come on.

803
01:14:02.652 --> 01:14:04.320
<i><font color="#ffff80">COMPUTER:</font>
Subject is contaminant-free.</i>

804
01:14:04.362 --> 01:14:06.572
<i>Zero contaminant factor.</i>

805
01:14:18.709 --> 01:14:20.586
Come on, come on.

806
01:14:21.420 --> 01:14:23.839
<i><font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Luther, what the he can we do?</i>

807
01:14:24.298 --> 01:14:25.591
What can we do?

808
01:14:26.509 --> 01:14:30.179
Hope he kills all the bugs before
the yellow dot gets to the red one.

809
01:15:22.023 --> 01:15:23.399
<i><font color="#ffff80">NEKHORVICH:</font> However we travel,</i>

810
01:15:23.441 --> 01:15:27.570
<i>I must arrive at my destination
within 20 hours of departure.</i>

811
01:15:32.950 --> 01:15:34.452
<i><font color="#ffff80">McCLOY:</font> How was I to know</i>

812
01:15:34.493 --> 01:15:37.204
<i>he needed treatment with Bellerophon
within 20 hours?</i>

813
01:15:42.793 --> 01:15:43.794
<font color="#ff8000">[GUNFIRE]</font>

814
01:16:01.353 --> 01:16:02.521
Get him.

815
01:16:25.503 --> 01:16:27.338
How much longer
before you can reach him?

816
01:16:27.421 --> 01:16:30.549
We got 29 seconds
before the generators turn off.

817
01:16:30.633 --> 01:16:32.676
Then Ethan'll be back on line.

818
01:16:37.848 --> 01:16:39.100
<font color="#ff8000">[TIMER BEEPING]</font>

819
01:16:47.399 --> 01:16:48.400
<font color="#ff8000">[GRUNTS]</font>

820
01:16:54.198 --> 01:16:55.199
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN SCREAMS]</font>

821
01:17:05.709 --> 01:17:06.710
<font color="#ff8000">[BEEPING CONTINUES]</font>

822
01:17:19.223 --> 01:17:20.558
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Luther!

823
01:17:53.424 --> 01:17:55.509
<font color="#ffff80">AMBROSE:</font> Hold your fire!

824
01:17:55.593 --> 01:17:57.678
Hold your fire, damn it!

825
01:17:57.928 --> 01:17:58.929
<font color="#ff8000">[SIGHS]</font>

826
01:18:12.276 --> 01:18:13.819
Well, Hunt,

827
01:18:15.905 --> 01:18:17.448
how you been?

828
01:18:21.035 --> 01:18:22.578
Fighting a bit of a cold.

829
01:18:25.539 --> 01:18:26.999
<font color="#ff8000">[LAUGHING]</font>

830
01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:30.753
That was the hardest part
of having to portray you,

831
01:18:30.961 --> 01:18:33.881
grinning like an idiot every 15 minutes.

832
01:18:35.341 --> 01:18:38.302
I always thought the hardest part
was curbing that pressing need of yours

833
01:18:38.344 --> 01:18:39.845
to get your gun off.

834
01:18:40.804 --> 01:18:43.641
You were in such a hurry
to knock off that 747,

835
01:18:43.682 --> 01:18:45.809
you never figured out
where Chimera really was.

836
01:18:46.185 --> 01:18:48.437
- I knew where it was.
- Oh.

837
01:18:49.063 --> 01:18:52.149
Then you knew the only way
Nekhorvich could smuggle the live virus

838
01:18:52.191 --> 01:18:53.484
was by injecting himself,

839
01:18:53.567 --> 01:18:55.778
and using his own bloodstream
as a petri dish.

840
01:18:55.819 --> 01:18:57.321
You knew that

841
01:18:58.113 --> 01:19:01.742
while you were knocking him off,
destroying the very thing you came for.

842
01:19:08.332 --> 01:19:10.459
Stop!

843
01:19:10.501 --> 01:19:12.336
Put a sock in it!

844
01:19:14.713 --> 01:19:18.259
Hit that bloody gun, and you'll spread
that virus all over the place!

845
01:19:19.468 --> 01:19:21.303
There it is, guys.

846
01:19:23.305 --> 01:19:24.848
The last of it.

847
01:19:25.975 --> 01:19:27.309
What was the top bid?

848
01:19:27.434 --> 01:19:29.937
Why?
You gonna make me a better offer?

849
01:19:30.437 --> 01:19:34.066
Than 37 million pounds? Not really.

850
01:19:35.234 --> 01:19:36.318
Oh.

851
01:19:36.819 --> 01:19:40.948
Somebody has been slipping you
our mail.

852
01:19:41.782 --> 01:19:45.369
Come on out here, you bad girl.

853
01:19:58.841 --> 01:20:00.551
She doesn't belong here.

854
01:20:00.801 --> 01:20:02.219
Let her go.

855
01:20:02.594 --> 01:20:08.225
She wouldn't be here
if it wasn't for you, Hunt.

856
01:20:15.524 --> 01:20:20.029
From this moment, you are responsible
for what happens to her.

857
01:20:20.070 --> 01:20:22.698
And if you're looking out
for her well-being,

858
01:20:22.740 --> 01:20:27.745
I suggest you advise her to pick up
the injection gun and bring it to me.

859
01:20:29.580 --> 01:20:31.874
The ball's in your court, Hunt.

860
01:20:35.461 --> 01:20:36.879
<font color="#ff8000">[LUTHER COUGHING]</font>

861
01:20:38.839 --> 01:20:40.632
Nyah's in the building.

862
01:20:41.175 --> 01:20:42.634
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> Do you copy?</i>

863
01:20:43.594 --> 01:20:44.887
Thank you.

864
01:21:01.278 --> 01:21:04.031
How do you know he won't shoot you
the minute he's got it?

865
01:21:04.698 --> 01:21:07.284
One can't hold Nyah responsible
for her actions.

866
01:21:07.368 --> 01:21:08.869
You know women, mate.

867
01:21:09.495 --> 01:21:11.372
Like monkeys they are.

868
01:21:11.747 --> 01:21:14.958
Won't let go of one branch
till they get a grip on the next.

869
01:21:17.669 --> 01:21:20.589
Get it, Nyah. I'll cover you.

870
01:21:52.663 --> 01:21:53.705
<font color="#ff8000">[SIGHS]</font>

871
01:21:53.789 --> 01:21:56.041
I am waiting.

872
01:22:07.177 --> 01:22:10.681
Things haven't exactly worked out
the way you thought they would, Ethan.

873
01:22:12.599 --> 01:22:13.892
Sorry.

874
01:22:30.701 --> 01:22:32.536
You bitch!

875
01:22:37.499 --> 01:22:38.959
<font color="#ff8000">[BEEPING]</font>

876
01:22:48.469 --> 01:22:52.347
You're not gonna shoot me, Sean.
Not this bitch.

877
01:22:52.556 --> 01:22:56.351
'Cause she's worth 37 million pounds.

878
01:22:58.187 --> 01:22:59.730
<font color="#ff8000">[HIGH PITCHED HUMMING]</font>

879
01:23:27.257 --> 01:23:30.844
- What did you think you were doing?
- I wasn't thinking!

880
01:23:31.220 --> 01:23:34.014
Just trying to stop you
from getting hurt, that's all.

881
01:23:34.765 --> 01:23:37.017
You who don't have a conscience.

882
01:23:37.643 --> 01:23:39.311
I guess I lied.

883
01:24:06.713 --> 01:24:09.091
You can't get us both out of here,
can you?

884
01:24:22.646 --> 01:24:24.606
I'm infected with Chimera.

885
01:24:24.648 --> 01:24:27.651
You know you don't have a choice.
Just do it.

886
01:24:29.111 --> 01:24:30.862
Do it. NOW!

887
01:24:51.341 --> 01:24:54.553
We've got 19 hours and 58 minutes.

888
01:24:54.720 --> 01:24:57.848
I'll get Bellerophon into your system
before then.

889
01:25:00.726 --> 01:25:04.771
Just stay alive!
I'm not going to lose you!

890
01:26:15.092 --> 01:26:17.552
Feel like pleading for your life?

891
01:26:22.933 --> 01:26:29.523
Well, then how about dying
so you can make me a lot of money.

892
01:26:35.737 --> 01:26:38.031
In just a few hours time

893
01:26:38.573 --> 01:26:42.994
you can be assured of going down
in history as the Typhoid Mary of Oz.

894
01:26:44.454 --> 01:26:45.789
Good day.

895
01:26:47.999 --> 01:26:49.000
<font color="#ff8000">[DOOR CLOSES]</font>

896
01:26:49.710 --> 01:26:52.963
There's not a chance of locating Nyah
until I can access the satellite.

897
01:26:53.004 --> 01:26:55.757
I can't do that till I get
this computer fixed,

898
01:26:55.799 --> 01:26:57.259
and that's taking a while.

899
01:26:57.300 --> 01:26:59.928
- How much time does she have left?
- Not long.

900
01:27:00.429 --> 01:27:04.141
- But Nyah will take care of Nyah.
- What do you mean?

901
01:27:04.224 --> 01:27:07.185
Unless we dose her with Bellerophon,
Nyah will kill herself.

902
01:27:08.770 --> 01:27:10.313
So first things first.

903
01:28:06.661 --> 01:28:09.039
<font color="#ffff80">BILLY:</font> Ambrose and his team
have arrived over the bridge,

904
01:28:09.122 --> 01:28:10.373
<i>and Nyah's not with him.</i>

905
01:28:10.457 --> 01:28:11.500
Copy that.

906
01:28:19.216 --> 01:28:22.928
You all right, mate?
Looks like heavy security from here.

907
01:28:23.720 --> 01:28:25.388
<i>What's it look like from there?</i>

908
01:28:27.516 --> 01:28:28.725
Risky.

909
01:29:13.520 --> 01:29:14.521
<font color="#ff8000">[GRATE SQUEAKING]</font>

910
01:29:35.834 --> 01:29:36.835
<font color="#ff8000">[GRUNTS]</font>

911
01:29:39.880 --> 01:29:40.881
<font color="#ff8000">[GROANS]</font>

912
01:29:47.721 --> 01:29:48.972
Simon.

913
01:29:51.391 --> 01:29:52.642
Stay here.

914
01:30:09.409 --> 01:30:11.578
<font color="#ffff80">ETHAN:</font> Breached the structure
at the 10:00 grating.

915
01:30:23.798 --> 01:30:27.719
It's a DNA match.
The blood's loaded with Chimera.

916
01:30:36.686 --> 01:30:39.314
And they certainly have Bellerophon.

917
01:30:40.690 --> 01:30:41.733
<font color="#ff8000">[SIGHS]</font>

918
01:30:41.816 --> 01:30:46.404
You've got the virus and the antivirus,
which means I've got 30 million for you.

919
01:30:46.613 --> 01:30:50.325
Not exactly.
We don't want just your cash.

920
01:30:50.367 --> 01:30:54.371
- What do you want?
- Stock, Mr. McCloy.

921
01:30:55.080 --> 01:30:58.375
Stock options
to be a little more precise.

922
01:30:59.167 --> 01:31:00.335
<font color="#ff8000">[CELL PHONE SPEED-DIALING]</font>

923
01:31:06.049 --> 01:31:09.928
Cut her loose right in the center of town.

924
01:31:10.303 --> 01:31:12.055
The more crowded, the better.

925
01:31:14.474 --> 01:31:15.892
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font>
Just picked up an Ambrose call.</i>

926
01:31:15.976 --> 01:31:17.477
Nyah's been dropped off.

927
01:31:17.560 --> 01:31:19.396
<i>- I think she's still alive.</i>
- Where is she?

928
01:31:19.938 --> 01:31:21.690
Somewhere in Sydney.

929
01:31:27.696 --> 01:31:28.905
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN GRUNTS]</font>

930
01:31:32.075 --> 01:31:34.786
Somewhere in Sydney?
Care to harden the target?

931
01:31:35.745 --> 01:31:39.249
<i><font color="#ffff80">LUTHER:</font> I can't until I can get the GPS
up on our computer. It's still down.</i>

932
01:31:39.290 --> 01:31:40.291
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN GROANS]</font>

933
01:31:41.334 --> 01:31:43.211
The clock is ticking.

934
01:31:44.045 --> 01:31:46.881
How quickly can you manufacture
more of the antivirus?

935
01:31:46.923 --> 01:31:49.718
- No time at all, once I've got it.
- Good.

936
01:31:49.968 --> 01:31:53.096
Biocyte stock is just a few weeks away
from going through the roof.

937
01:31:53.138 --> 01:31:55.890
- What are you talking about?
- An outbreak of Chimera.

938
01:31:56.057 --> 01:31:59.728
- Where?
- Downtown Sydney, for a start.

939
01:31:59.894 --> 01:32:03.398
You create the supply, Mr. McCloy.
We've just created the demand.

940
01:32:03.440 --> 01:32:07.569
Three million people in Sydney
and 17 million people in Australia

941
01:32:07.610 --> 01:32:10.363
are going to need Bellerophon
within the next few days.

942
01:32:10.488 --> 01:32:12.282
Not to mention the rest of the world.

943
01:32:12.824 --> 01:32:14.951
Now, this is how it's going to work.

944
01:32:15.452 --> 01:32:18.121
- The shares outstanding are?
- 93.4 million.

945
01:32:18.163 --> 01:32:19.581
Which means, Mr. McCloy,

946
01:32:19.622 --> 01:32:23.418
we need to get our hands
on 480,000 options.

947
01:32:23.460 --> 01:32:26.296
We'll borrow your 30 million
to buy those options.

948
01:32:26.379 --> 01:32:29.758
Your stock has never sold
above $31 a share.

949
01:32:29.841 --> 01:32:33.970
When your stock goes north of 200,
which it will,

950
01:32:34.054 --> 01:32:36.222
those options will be worth billions,

951
01:32:36.389 --> 01:32:41.686
and I will own 51 percent of Biocyte.

952
01:32:41.895 --> 01:32:43.480
This is outrageous.

953
01:32:44.481 --> 01:32:47.776
I will not let you take control
of my company.

954
01:32:48.318 --> 01:32:50.361
Sit down.

955
01:33:19.808 --> 01:33:20.809
<font color="#ff8000">[MAN GRUNTS]</font>

956
01:33:30.151 --> 01:33:33.196
You'll be a billionaire.
That's better than being broke.

957
01:33:33.238 --> 01:33:36.199
I have terrorists
and other pharmaceutical companies

958
01:33:36.241 --> 01:33:37.492
standing in line.

959
01:33:43.748 --> 01:33:46.251
The ball's in your court, Mr. McCloy.

960
01:33:52.340 --> 01:33:54.509
<font color="#ff8000">[CLATTERING]</font>

961
01:34:41.264 --> 01:34:44.058
Run that bastard down.

962
01:34:55.570 --> 01:34:56.571
<font color="#ff8000">[BANGING]</font>

963
01:34:58.448 --> 01:35:01.409
